== Fear Me, Wicked Record Execs ==
In which our columnist discovers the latest in genius MP3 software, and
may never buy a new CD again
(By Mark Morford)
http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/g/a/2003/01/08/notes010803.DTL&nl=fix


Oh sure there's the free downloading of music. Of course you already
know this.

Oh sure there's full-fledged software, flicks, games, porn, CDs, Iraqi
bombing stratagems, the alien code to Dick Cheney's demonic
defibrillator, all available online for downloading right now, if you
have the correct software and a righteous sense of entertainment-media
injustice and a really big hard drive and enormous amounts of free time
which of course you don't because you're not, like, a geek or something.
Right?

But of course you know about MP3 downloads. Napster. KaZaA. Yay. Song
swapping as rebellion, as pop-culture revolution, as a way to really
piss off Lars Ulrich. Then came the swift sword of dumb justice. And
Napster went poof. But KaZaA and its brethren still thrive. 

http://www.kazaa.com

As do cheapass CD burners, and DVD burners, and spindles of 100 blank
CDs for pennies apiece, all immediately followed by the increasing
realization that, Jesus with a 20GB iPod, record companies and movie
studios and etc. really have been ripping us off for, you know,
millennia. Twenty bucks for the new Coldplay CD? Only 75 cents of which
actually goes to the band? Something's got to change.

Now there is StreamRipperX for Mac. There's also equivalent software for
PCs, but I worship at the altar of Apple and the PowerBook Titanium and
hence know very little of Windows software and cringe at the bloated
bug-ridden inelegance of Microsoft so therefore I speak only of Mac. But
Windows people also know this to be very true.

http://download.com.com/3000-2182-10165388.html?tag=list

StreamRipperX is genius. StreamRipperX is the next tiny but dazzling
step in the media revolution currently terrifying AOL/Time
Warner/Disney/Viacom execs and their Range Rover dealers.

StreamRipperX is, very simply, a tiny piece of software for the Mac that
records live, continuous MP3 audio streams from Net radio stations,
automatically breaks up the songs they play into individual,
high-quality, discrete MP3 files, names them and then lets you listen,
organize, burn custom CDs, whatever. All free. 

This is all it does. It is very simple. But it is, quite simply, the
greatest thing ever in this lifetime ever. Think about it.

Here's an example of what you can do right now: Click on one of hundreds
of DJ-free, 24-hour online music stations of a particular, favorite
genre, leave StreamRipper running for a few hours (or all day) and come
back later -- and, boom, waiting for you is a couple gigs of fresh new
music, hours and hours worth, all organized by song name and group,
ready to burn right to CD. Amazing. So much for Napster.

http://www.shoutcast.com

In fact, StreamRipperX is running right now, as I type this column,
recording a live stream from Groove Salad Net radio, a downtempo/chill
station from SomaFM. The program has recorded, named and sorted a dozen
new songs just in the past eight paragraphs. And all I do is listen,
toss the songs I don't like and expand my music collection.
Effortlessly.

http://www.somafm.com/

Of course, this is all immoral and evil and short-changes the artists
involved, screws them out of royalties and rent money and pot money and
so forth, hurts the economy, causes AOL/Time Warner stock to whimper and
Steve Case to forgo buying his eighth Ferrari of the month. Right? Your
conscience says so. Something isn't quite fair about all this, it says.
Well, maybe.

Or maybe not. Maybe that's just the industry talking, guilting you into
false belief. Maybe programs like StreamRipperX, which is free and small
and elegant and effortless to use and, um, free, spreads the music
around, exposes artists to new audiences, widens the artistic purview,
cuts out the money-grubbing middleman and allows art, like information,
to be fluid and free.

Maybe such software redefines the popular culture just a little, forces
long-staid, paranoid, litigious, stagnant industries to scramble and
move and figure out new, hopefully more fair, methods by which to
support new artists and pay them to create and still make a decent
enough profit without making consumers feel like altar boys in the
Boston Archdiocese. Can I get a hell yeah?

Of course, StreamRipperX is only the most current and most brilliant
step in a very fast-moving technological evolution. It will be obsolete
within a year, replaced by something even better -- digital, insanely
fast, veritably orgiastic in its potential entertainment offerings,
on-demand everything, with the PC as the hub, and you at the helm.

But of course all that's happening now is panic. Hand-wringing.
Scowling. Lawsuits galore. Frantic CD and DVD encryption technology that
gets immediately hacked by yawning teenagers. Failing for-pay
music-downloading sites sponsored by angry record companies. How very
1996 of them.

http://sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/n/a/2003/01/07/international0746EST0496.DTL&nl=fix

There are other ways. There are new paradigms by which money can be made
and artists can thrive and record companies can become more nimble and
smart and you can still dance naked in your living room to gobs of free
digital music pumping from your Net-connected speakers. 

Like solar power and 75-mpg cars and 5-year lightbulbs and naturopathic
medicine and gay marriage, the ideas are there, the technology is in
place, but the oppression and disinfo are rampant, as the biz is
hell-bent on keeping its angry fist wrapped around its dwindling
dollars. 

Like the movie industry (which is next on the list to face similar tech
anarchy), the record biz hasn't had to fundamentally change, well, ever.
StreamRipperX and its brethren are merely more reminders that it's about
time they did. Hell yeah.


